05455nam a22011295i 9780823283774DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232837747 a10.1515/97808232837742doi  a(DE-B1597)550882  a(OCoLC)1090540097  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHM1116 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a303.62231 aCrépon, Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMurderous Consent :bOn the Accommodation of Violent Death /cMarc Crépon. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- t1. Justice -- t2. Life -- t3. Freedom -- t4. Truth -- t5. The World -- tConclusion -- tAppendix. Friendship: A Trial by History -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMurderous Consent details our implication in violence we do not directly inflict but in which we are structurally complicit: famines, civil wars, political repression in far-away places, and war, as it's classically understood. Marc Crépon insists on a bond between ethics and politics and attributes violence to our treatment of the two as separate spheres. We repeatedly resist the call to responsibility, as expressed by the appeal-by peoples across the world-for the care and attention that their vulnerability enjoins. But Crépon argues that this resistance is not ineluctable, and the book searches for ways that enable us to mitigate it, through rebellion, kindness, irony, critique, and shame. In the process, he engages with a range of writers, from Camus, Sartre, and Freud, to Stefan Zweig and Karl Kraus, to Kenzaburo Oe, Emmanuel Levinas and Judith Butler. The resulting exchange between philosophy and literature enables Crépon to delineate the contours of a possible/impossible ethicosmopolitics-an ethicosmopolitics to come.Pushing against the limits of liberal rationalism, Crépon calls for a more radical understanding of interpersonal responsibility. Not just a work of philosophy but an engagement with life as it's lived, Murderous Consent works to redefine our global obligations, articulating anew what humanitarianism demands and what an ethically grounded political resistance might mean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aPolitical ethics. 0aViolencexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aViolencexPolitical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aCamus.  aEinstein famine.  aFreud.  aGünther Anders.  aHolocaust.  aKarl Kraus.  aKenzaburo Oe.  aLevinas.  aMerleau-Ponty.  aSartre.  aVasily Grossman.  aanimal rights.  acivilization.  acontinental philosophy.  acosmopolitanism.  adeconstruction.  aethics.  aexistentialism.  agenocide.  ahuman rights.  ahumanitarianism.  aidentity politics.  aideology.  ainternational ethics.  ainternational justice.  anationalism.  anuclear warfare.  aotherness.  apolitical philosophy.  apolitical theory.  arebellion.  arefugees.  awar.1 aMartel, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Jacob.1 aLoriaux, Michael.1 aMartel, James.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823283774zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823283774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823283774.jpg  a978-